Here's how to save and restore draft text using Window lifecycle events:

**Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new MainPage());
}

public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        SaveDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        SaveDraft(); // Android back-button can skip Stopped
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        if (Page is MainPage mainPage)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", mainPage.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    private void RestoreDraft()
    {
        if (Page is MainPage mainPage)
            mainPage.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }
}
```

**In your ViewModel:**

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string draftText = string.Empty;

    public NoteViewModel()
    {
        // Restore on initial load too
        DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnStopped`** — fires when the app is fully backgrounded; save here.
- **`OnResumed`** — fires when returning from background; restore here.
- **`OnDestroying`** — also save here because Android's back button can skip `Stopped`.
- **`Resumed` does NOT fire on first launch** — so also load the draft in your constructor.
- Keep handlers fast (use `Preferences` for small strings, not DB writes) to avoid ANR/watchdog kills.
